01:16.541 --> 01:18.842
<i>We are in an unbalanced</i>

01:18.844 --> 01:23.047
<i>and inequivalent confrontation between democracies</i>

01:23.049 --> 01:25.416
<i>who are obliged to play by the rules</i>

01:26.051 --> 01:29.486
<i>and entities who think democracy is a joke.</i>

01:31.590 --> 01:33.958
You can't convince fanatics

01:33.960 --> 01:38.562
by saying, "hey, hatred paralyzes you,

01:38.564 --> 01:40.164
love releases you."

01:41.266 --> 01:45.536
There are different rules that we have to play by.

02:01.119 --> 02:03.787
Female newsreader: <i>Today, two of Iran's top nuclear scientists</i>

02:03.789 --> 02:05.756
<i>were targeted by hit squads.</i>

02:05.758 --> 02:07.791
Female newsreader 2: <i>...In the capital Tehran.</i>

02:07.793 --> 02:09.425
Male newsreader: <i>...The latest in a string of attacks.</i>

02:09.428 --> 02:11.662
Female newsreader 3: <i>Today's attack has all the hallmarks</i>

02:11.664 --> 02:13.831
<i>of major strategic sabotage.</i>

02:13.833 --> 02:14.932
Female newsreader 4: <i>Iran immediately accused</i>

02:14.934 --> 02:16.166
<i>the U.S. and Israel</i>

02:16.168 --> 02:18.035
<i>of trying to damage its nuclear program.</i>

02:18.336 --> 02:19.700
Mahmoud Ahmadinejad:

02:19.700 --> 02:20.889
Unfortunately, and without any doubt,

02:21.140 --> 02:23.600
in the assassinations
which took place today

02:23.934 --> 02:27.774
Western countries and the
Zionist regime were involved.

02:28.080 --> 02:33.817
I want to categorically deny any United States involvement

02:33.819 --> 02:38.756
in any kind of act of violence inside Iran.

02:38.758 --> 02:41.925
Covert actions can help,

02:41.927 --> 02:43.927
can assist.

02:45.196 --> 02:48.098
They are needed, they are not all the time essential,

02:48.333 --> 02:52.770
and they, in no way, can replace political wisdom.

02:53.138 --> 02:55.372
Alex Gibney: Were the assassinations in Iran

02:55.374 --> 02:57.775
related to the STUXnet computer attacks?

02:58.943 --> 03:00.778
Uh, next question, please.

03:02.380 --> 03:03.947
Male newsreader: <i>Iran's infrastructure</i>

03:03.949 --> 03:05.049
<i>is being targeted</i>

03:05.051 --> 03:08.218
<i>by a new and dangerously powerful cyber worm.</i>

03:08.220 --> 03:10.854
The so-called STUXnet worm is specifically designed,

03:10.856 --> 03:13.190
it seems, to infiltrate and sabotage

03:13.192 --> 03:16.326
<i>real-world power plants and factories and refineries.</i>

03:16.328 --> 03:17.728
Male newsreader 2: <i>It's not trying to steal information</i>

03:17.730 --> 03:18.896
<i>or grab your credit card,</i>

03:18.898 --> 03:21.699
<i>they're trying to get into some sort of industrial plant</i>

03:21.701 --> 03:24.085
<i>and wreak havoc trying to blow up an engine or...</i>

03:24.085 --> 03:25.376
The Stuxnet virus
has made attacks worldwide.

03:25.376 --> 03:26.788
Male newsreader 3:

03:26.788 --> 03:31.585
In Iran alone it was identified
30 thousand times.

03:32.336 --> 03:37.336
A super computer virus has put on alert
several countries' secret services.

03:37.591 --> 03:40.551
The information could be
in the reach of terrorists.

03:40.552 --> 03:41.652
Male newsreader 4: <i>No one knows</i>

03:41.654 --> 03:42.820
<i>who's behind the worm</i>

03:42.822 --> 03:44.488
<i>and the exact nature of its mission,</i>

03:44.490 --> 03:47.357
<i>but there are fears Iran will hold Israel</i>

03:47.359 --> 03:50.728
<i>or America responsible and seek retaliation.</i>

03:50.730 --> 03:51.829
Male newsreader 5: <i>It's not impossible that</i>

03:51.831 --> 03:53.163
<i>some group of hackers did it,</i>

03:53.165 --> 03:55.232
<i>but the security experts that are studying this</i>

03:55.234 --> 03:58.001
<i>really think this required the resource of a nation-state.</i>

04:03.942 --> 04:05.876
Man: Okay, and spinning.

04:05.878 --> 04:07.344
Gibney: Okay, good. Here we go.

04:08.580 --> 04:11.882
What impact, ultimately, did the STUXnet attack have?

04:11.884 --> 04:13.150
Can you say?

04:13.952 --> 04:16.120
I don't want to get into the details.

04:16.353 --> 04:18.856
Gibney: Since the event has already happened,

04:18.858 --> 04:22.559
why can't we talk more openly and publicly about STUXnet?

04:22.561 --> 04:25.462
Yeah, I mean, my answer is because it's classified.

04:25.930 --> 04:29.032
I... I won't knowledge... you know, knowingly

04:29.034 --> 04:31.135
offer up anything I consider classified.

04:31.137 --> 04:33.370
Gibney: I know that you can't talk much about STUXnet,

04:33.372 --> 04:36.774
because STUXnet is officially classified.

04:36.776 --> 04:38.142
You're right on both those counts.

04:38.610 --> 04:39.943
Gibney: But there has been

04:39.945 --> 04:42.045
a lot reported about it in the press.

04:42.047 --> 04:44.281
I don't want to comment on this.

04:44.283 --> 04:48.552
I read it in the newspaper, the media, like you,

04:48.554 --> 04:51.555
but I'm unable to elaborate upon it.

04:51.790 --> 04:53.957
People might find it frustrating

04:53.959 --> 04:56.493
not to be able to talk about it when it's in the public domain,

04:56.495 --> 04:57.895
but...

04:57.897 --> 04:59.396
Gibney: I find it frustrating.

04:59.398 --> 05:00.898
Yeah, I'm sure you do.

05:00.900 --> 05:02.466
I don't answer that question.

05:02.468 --> 05:03.834
Unfortunately, I can't comment.

05:03.836 --> 05:05.469
I do not know how to answer that.

05:05.471 --> 05:07.638
Two answers before you even get started, I don't know,

05:07.640 --> 05:10.440
and if I did, we wouldn't talk about it anyway.

05:10.442 --> 05:12.276
Gibney: How can you have a debate if everything's secret?

05:12.278 --> 05:14.311
I think right now that's just where we are.

05:14.612 --> 05:16.079
No one wants to...

05:16.081 --> 05:18.482
Countries aren't happy about confessing

05:18.484 --> 05:21.285
or owning up to what they did because they're not quite sure

05:21.287 --> 05:23.153
where they want the system to go.

05:23.788 --> 05:25.756
<i>And so whoever was behind STUXnet</i>

05:25.758 --> 05:27.257
<i>hasn't admitted they were behind it.</i>

05:31.095 --> 05:32.963
Gibney: <i>Asking officials about STUXnet</i>

05:32.965 --> 05:34.498
<i>was frustrating and surreal,</i>

05:34.799 --> 05:37.334
<i>like asking the emperor about his new clothes.</i>

05:38.036 --> 05:41.138
<i>Even after the cyber weapon had penetrated computers</i>

05:41.140 --> 05:42.539
<i>all over the world,</i>

05:42.807 --> 05:45.108
<i>no one was willing to admit it was loose</i>

05:45.110 --> 05:47.511
<i>or talk about the dangers it posed.</i>

05:48.379 --> 05:50.647
<i>What was it about the STUXnet operation</i>

05:50.649 --> 05:52.449
<i>that was hiding in plain sight?</i>

05:53.885 --> 05:55.652
<i>Maybe there was a way the computer code</i>

05:55.654 --> 05:57.287
<i>could speak for itself.</i>

05:58.056 --> 06:00.424
<i>STUXnet first surfaced in Belarus.</i>

06:00.992 --> 06:03.360
<i>I started with a call to the man who discovered it</i>

06:03.362 --> 06:06.363
<i>when his clients in Iran began to panic</i>

06:06.365 --> 06:09.032
<i>over an epidemic of computer shutdowns.</i>

06:09.834 --> 06:13.070
Had you ever seen anything quite so sophisticated before?

06:13.664 --> 06:17.424
I have seen very sophisticated
viruses before,

06:17.668 --> 06:21.548
but they didn't have...

06:24.008 --> 06:25.378
this kind of...

06:26.969 --> 06:27.719
zero day.

06:29.054 --> 06:32.524
It was the first time in my practice.

06:33.350 --> 06:36.440
That led me to understand

06:37.813 --> 06:44.783
that I should notify
web security companies ASAP

06:46.530 --> 06:51.030
about the fact that such a danger exists.

07:36.487 --> 07:38.322
Eric Chien: <i>On a daily basis, basically</i>

07:38.324 --> 07:40.390
<i>we are sifting through</i>

07:40.392 --> 07:43.894
<i>a massive haystack looking for that proverbial needle.</i>

07:44.762 --> 07:47.731
We get millions of pieces of new malicious threats

07:47.733 --> 07:49.599
and there are millions of attacks going on

07:49.601 --> 07:50.801
every single day.

07:50.969 --> 07:53.403
And only way are trying to protect people

07:53.405 --> 07:55.005
and their computers and... and their systems

07:55.007 --> 07:57.674
and countries' infrastructure

07:57.676 --> 07:59.776
from being taken down by those attacks.

07:59.778 --> 08:03.113
But more importantly, we have to find the attacks that matter.

08:03.115 --> 08:04.848
When you're talking about that many,

08:05.149 --> 08:07.417
impact is extremely important.

08:19.797 --> 08:21.498
Eugene Kaspersky: <i>Twenty years ago, the antivirus companies,</i>

08:21.500 --> 08:23.200
they were hunting for computer viruses

08:23.202 --> 08:24.468
because there were not so many.

08:24.470 --> 08:27.771
So we had, like, tens of dozens a month,

08:27.972 --> 08:30.540
and there was just little numbers.

08:30.542 --> 08:34.745
Now, we collect millions of unique attacks every month.

08:36.114 --> 08:38.548
Vitaly Kamluk: <i>This room we call a woodpecker's room</i>

08:38.549 --> 08:39.883
<i>or a virus lab,</i>

08:40.118 --> 08:42.052
and this is where <i>virus analysts sit.</i>

08:42.054 --> 08:44.020
<i>We call them woodpeckers because they are</i>

08:44.023 --> 08:46.523
<i>pecking the worms, network worms, and viruses.</i>

08:47.392 --> 08:50.627
<i>And we see, like, three different groups of hackers</i>

08:50.629 --> 08:52.195
behind cyber-attacks.

08:52.964 --> 08:54.731
They are traditional cyber criminals.

08:54.899 --> 08:58.735
Those guys are interested only in illegal profit.

08:58.737 --> 09:00.137
And quick and dirty money.

09:00.139 --> 09:02.305
<i>Activists, or hacktivists,</i>

09:02.307 --> 09:04.674
<i>they are hacking for fun or hacking to push</i>

09:04.676 --> 09:05.942
<i>some political message.</i>

09:06.177 --> 09:08.545
<i>And the third group is nation-states.</i>

09:08.746 --> 09:11.648
<i>They're interested in high-quality intelligence</i>

09:11.650 --> 09:13.083
<i>or sabotage activity.</i>

09:14.352 --> 09:16.853
Chien: <i>Security companies not only share information</i>

09:16.855 --> 09:18.588
<i>but we also share binary samples.</i>

09:18.590 --> 09:20.190
<i>So when this threat was found</i>

09:20.192 --> 09:22.025
<i>by a Belarusian security company</i>

09:22.027 --> 09:24.361
<i>on one of their customer's machines in Iran,</i>

09:24.363 --> 09:26.963
<i>the sample was shared amongst the security community.</i>

09:27.865 --> 09:29.433
When we try to name threats, we just try to pick

09:29.435 --> 09:31.501
some sort of string, some sort of words,

09:31.503 --> 09:34.071
<i>that are inside of the binary.</i>

09:35.239 --> 09:37.607
<i>In this case, there was a couple of words in there</i>

09:37.609 --> 09:40.577
<i>and we took pieces of each, and that formed STUXnet.</i>

09:43.047 --> 09:46.249
I got the news about STUXnet from one of my engineers.

09:46.251 --> 09:48.952
He came to my office, opened the door,

09:49.520 --> 09:52.522
and he said, "so, Eugene, of course you know that

09:52.524 --> 09:55.125
we are waiting for something really bad.

09:55.426 --> 09:56.593
It happened."

10:03.301 --> 10:05.469
Gibney: <i>Give me some sense of what it was like</i>

10:05.471 --> 10:06.870
in the lab at that time.

10:06.872 --> 10:08.472
Was there a palpable sense of amazement

10:08.474 --> 10:10.474
that you had something really different there?

10:10.775 --> 10:12.776
Well, I wouldn't call it amazement.

10:12.778 --> 10:14.845
It was a kind of a shock.

10:15.246 --> 10:18.381
It went beyond our worst fears, our worst nightmares,

10:18.749 --> 10:21.751
and this continued the more we analyzed.

10:21.753 --> 10:23.720
The more we researched,

10:23.722 --> 10:26.723
the more bizarre the whole story got.

10:27.058 --> 10:28.725
We look at so much malware every day that

10:28.727 --> 10:30.660
we can just look at the code and straightaway we can say,

10:30.662 --> 10:32.262
"okay, there's something bad going on here,

10:32.264 --> 10:33.730
and I need to investigate that."

10:33.732 --> 10:34.798
And that's the way it was

10:34.999 --> 10:36.933
when we looked at STUXnet for the first time.

10:36.935 --> 10:39.436
We opened it up and there was just bad things everywhere.

10:39.438 --> 10:41.905
Just like, okay, this is bad and that's bad,

10:41.907 --> 10:43.440
and, you know, we need to investigate this.

10:43.442 --> 10:44.908
And just suddenly we had, like,

10:44.910 --> 10:46.376
a hundred questions straightaway.

10:48.412 --> 10:50.847
<i>The most interesting thing that we do is detective work</i>

10:50.849 --> 10:53.517
<i>where we try to track down who's behind a threat,</i>

10:53.519 --> 10:55.085
<i>what are they doing, what's their motivation,</i>

10:55.087 --> 10:56.820
<i>and try to really stop it at the root.</i>

10:56.822 --> 10:59.189
<i>And it is kind of all-consuming.</i>

10:59.191 --> 11:00.824
<i>You get this new puzzle</i>

11:00.826 --> 11:02.526
<i>and it's very difficult to put it down,</i>

11:02.528 --> 11:04.961
<i>you know, work until, like, 4:00 am in the morning</i>

11:04.963 --> 11:06.163
<i>and figure these things out.</i>

11:06.165 --> 11:08.965
<i>And I was in that zone where I was very consumed by this,</i>

11:08.967 --> 11:11.101
<i>very excited about it, very interested to know</i>

11:11.103 --> 11:12.369
<i>what was happening.</i>

11:12.371 --> 11:15.505
<i>And Eric was also in that same sort of zone.</i>

11:15.507 --> 11:18.208
<i>So the two of us were, like, back and forth all the time.</i>

11:18.210 --> 11:20.944
Chien: <i>Liam and I continued to grind at the code,</i>

11:20.946 --> 11:23.046
<i>sharing pieces, comparing notes,</i>

11:23.048 --> 11:24.881
<i>bouncing ideas off of each other.</i>

11:25.316 --> 11:26.783
<i>We realized that we needed to do</i>

11:26.785 --> 11:29.853
<i>what we called deep analysis, pick apart the threat,</i>

11:29.855 --> 11:32.689
<i>every single byte, every single zero, one,</i>

11:32.691 --> 11:34.791
<i>and understand everything that was inside of it.</i>

11:35.326 --> 11:37.127
<i>And just to give you some context,</i>

11:37.129 --> 11:39.162
we can go through and understand every line of code

11:39.164 --> 11:40.964
for the average threat in minutes.

11:41.566 --> 11:43.366
And here we are one month into this threat

11:43.368 --> 11:45.302
and we were just starting to discover what we call

11:45.304 --> 11:47.204
the payload or its whole purpose.

11:49.540 --> 11:51.074
<i>When looking at the STUXnet code,</i>

11:51.076 --> 11:53.643
<i>it's 20 times the size of the average piece of code</i>

11:54.145 --> 11:56.379
<i>but contains almost no bugs inside of it.</i>

11:56.381 --> 11:58.248
<i>And that's extremely rare.</i>

11:58.250 --> 12:00.150
<i>Malicious code always has bugs inside of it.</i>

12:00.152 --> 12:01.918
<i>This wasn't the case with STUXnet.</i>

12:01.920 --> 12:04.754
<i>It's dense and every piece of code does something</i>

12:04.756 --> 12:07.591
<i>and does something right in order to conduct its attack.</i>

12:08.826 --> 12:10.894
<i>One of the things that surprised us</i>

12:10.896 --> 12:13.263
<i>was that STUXnet utilized what's called</i>

12:13.265 --> 12:15.832
a zero-day exploit, or basically,

12:15.834 --> 12:18.168
a piece of code that allows it to spread

12:18.170 --> 12:20.003
without you having to do anything.

12:20.005 --> 12:22.739
You don't have to, for example, download a file and run it.

12:22.741 --> 12:24.941
A zero-day exploit is an exploit that

12:24.943 --> 12:26.610
nobody knows about except the attacker.

12:26.612 --> 12:28.178
So there's no protection against it.

12:28.180 --> 12:29.613
There's been no patch released.

12:29.615 --> 12:31.915
There's been zero days protection,

12:31.917 --> 12:33.516
you know, against it.

12:34.385 --> 12:35.785
<i>That's what attackers value,</i>

12:35.787 --> 12:37.587
<i>because they know 100 percent</i>

12:37.589 --> 12:39.923
<i>if they have this zero-day exploit,</i>

12:39.925 --> 12:41.625
<i>they can get in wherever they want.</i>

12:41.627 --> 12:43.126
<i>They're actually very valuable.</i>

12:43.128 --> 12:44.527
<i>You can sell these on the underground</i>

12:44.529 --> 12:46.049
<i>for hundreds of thousands of dollars.</i>

12:47.398 --> 12:48.465
Chien: <i>Then we became more worried</i>

12:48.467 --> 12:50.533
<i>because immediately we discovered more zero days.</i>

12:50.535 --> 12:53.270
And again, these zero days are extremely rare.

12:53.272 --> 12:55.572
Inside STUXnet we had, you know, four zero days,

12:55.574 --> 12:57.307
and for the entire rest of the year,

12:57.309 --> 12:59.876
we only saw 12 zero days used.

12:59.878 --> 13:01.544
It blows all... everything else out of the water.

13:01.546 --> 13:02.779
We've never seen this before.

13:02.781 --> 13:04.541
Actually, we've never seen it since, either.

13:04.615 --> 13:07.217
Seeing one in a malware you could understand

13:07.219 --> 13:10.120
because, you know, the malware authors are making money,

13:10.122 --> 13:11.721
they're stealing people's credit cards and making money,

13:11.723 --> 13:12.889
so it's worth their while to use it,

13:12.891 --> 13:15.258
but seeing four zero days, could be worth

13:15.260 --> 13:16.459
half a million dollars right there,

13:16.461 --> 13:18.228
used in one piece of malware,

13:18.496 --> 13:20.897
this is not your ordinary criminal gangs doing this.

13:20.899 --> 13:22.499
This is... this is someone bigger.

13:22.501 --> 13:24.401
It's definitely not traditional crime,

13:24.403 --> 13:27.904
not hacktivists. Who else?

13:28.773 --> 13:31.007
It was evident on a very early stage

13:31.509 --> 13:33.743
that just given the sophistication

13:33.745 --> 13:35.245
of this malware...

13:36.480 --> 13:39.282
Suggested that there must have been

13:39.284 --> 13:40.750
a nation-state involved,

13:40.752 --> 13:43.987
at least one nation-state involved in the development.

13:43.989 --> 13:46.022
When we look at code that's coming from

13:46.024 --> 13:47.590
what appears to be a state attacker

13:47.592 --> 13:50.193
or state-sponsored attacker, usually they're scrubbed clean.

13:50.195 --> 13:52.629
They don't... they don't leave little bits behind.

13:52.631 --> 13:54.364
They don't leave little hints behind.

13:54.632 --> 13:56.299
<i>But in STUXnet there were actually</i>

13:56.301 --> 13:57.667
<i>a few hints left behind.</i>

13:58.936 --> 14:02.205
<i>One was that, in order to get low-level access</i>

14:02.207 --> 14:03.673
<i>to Microsoft Windows,</i>

14:03.874 --> 14:05.674
<i>STUXnet needed to use a digital certificate,</i>

14:05.976 --> 14:08.378
<i>which certifies that this piece of code</i>

14:08.380 --> 14:11.247
<i>came from a particular company.</i>

14:12.149 --> 14:14.217
Now, those attackers obviously couldn't go to Microsoft

14:14.219 --> 14:15.685
and say, "hey, test our code out for us.

14:15.687 --> 14:17.287
And give us a digital certificate."

14:17.988 --> 14:19.589
So they essentially stole them...

14:20.825 --> 14:22.892
<i>From two companies in Taiwan.</i>

14:22.894 --> 14:24.794
<i>And these two companies have nothing to do with each other</i>

14:24.796 --> 14:26.463
<i>except for their close proximity</i>

14:26.465 --> 14:28.264
<i>in the exact same business park.</i>

14:30.835 --> 14:34.671
<i>Digital certificates are guarded very, very closely</i>

14:34.673 --> 14:36.206
<i>behind multiple doors</i>

14:36.208 --> 14:38.641
<i>and they require multiple people to unlock.</i>

14:38.643 --> 14:40.310
Security: <i> ...To the camera.</i>

14:40.312 --> 14:42.011
Chien: <i>And they need to provide both biometrics</i>

14:42.013 --> 14:44.414
<i>- and, as well, pass phrases.</i>

14:44.416 --> 14:45.882
<i>It wasn't like those certificates were</i>

14:45.884 --> 14:47.584
<i>just sitting on some machine connected to the Internet.</i>

14:47.818 --> 14:50.620
<i>Some human assets had to be involved, spies.</i>

14:50.855 --> 14:52.689
O'Murchu: <i>Like a cleaner who comes in at night</i>

14:52.691 --> 14:54.424
<i>and has stolen these certificates</i>

14:54.426 --> 14:55.658
<i>from these companies.</i>

14:59.063 --> 15:01.164
It did feel like walking onto the set

15:01.166 --> 15:03.666
of this James Bond movie and you...

15:03.668 --> 15:05.235
You've been embroiled in this thing that,

15:05.237 --> 15:07.837
you know, you... you never expected.

15:10.508 --> 15:11.608
<i>We continued to search,</i>

15:11.610 --> 15:13.109
<i>and we continued to search in code,</i>

15:13.111 --> 15:15.945
<i>and eventually we found some other bread crumbs left</i>

15:15.947 --> 15:17.347
<i>we were able to follow.</i>

15:18.048 --> 15:19.682
<i>It was doing something with Siemens,</i>

15:19.950 --> 15:22.752
<i>Siemens software, possibly Siemens hardware.</i>

15:23.053 --> 15:24.754
We'd never ever seen that in any malware before,

15:24.756 --> 15:26.089
something targeting Siemens.

15:26.091 --> 15:28.051
We didn't even know why they would be doing that.

15:29.627 --> 15:32.362
<i>But after googling, very quickly we understood</i>

15:32.364 --> 15:34.798
<i>it was targeting Siemens PLCs.</i>

15:35.266 --> 15:38.201
STUXnet was targeting a very specific hardware device,

15:38.203 --> 15:41.604
something called a PLC or a programmable logic controller.

15:42.039 --> 15:44.941
Langner: <i>The PLC is kind of a very small computer</i>

15:45.242 --> 15:47.977
attached to physical equipment,

15:47.979 --> 15:50.613
like pumps, like valves, like motors.

15:51.415 --> 15:55.985
<i>So this little box is running a digital program</i>

15:55.987 --> 15:58.288
<i>and the actions of this program</i>

15:58.290 --> 16:02.392
<i>turns that motor on, off, or sets a specific speed.</i>

16:02.394 --> 16:04.127
Chien: <i>Those program module controllers</i>

16:04.129 --> 16:06.663
<i>control things like power plants, power grids.</i>

16:06.665 --> 16:08.398
O'Murchu: <i>This is used in factories,</i>

16:08.400 --> 16:10.867
<i>it's used in critical infrastructure.</i>

16:11.569 --> 16:14.604
Critical infrastructure, it's everywhere around us,

16:14.606 --> 16:17.173
<i>transportation, telecommunications,</i>

16:17.175 --> 16:19.476
<i>financial services, health care.</i>

16:20.010 --> 16:22.912
<i>So the payload of STUXnet was designed</i>

16:22.914 --> 16:26.082
to attack some very important part

16:26.084 --> 16:27.517
of our world.

16:27.785 --> 16:29.319
The payload is gonna be important.

16:29.321 --> 16:32.088
What happens there could be very dangerous.

16:34.292 --> 16:37.260
Langner: <i>The next very big surprise came</i>

16:37.262 --> 16:39.562
<i>when it infected our lab system.</i>

16:40.297 --> 16:43.299
<i>We figured out that the malware was probing</i>

16:43.301 --> 16:44.667
<i>for controllers.</i>

16:45.035 --> 16:47.103
<i>It was quite picky on its targets.</i>

16:47.105 --> 16:51.441
<i>It didn't try to manipulate any given controller in a network</i>

16:51.443 --> 16:52.775
<i>that it would see.</i>

16:53.010 --> 16:57.213
<i>It went through several checks, and when those checks failed,</i>

16:57.215 --> 16:59.449
<i>it would not implement the attack.</i>

17:02.186 --> 17:06.055
<i>It was obviously probing for a specific target.</i>

17:07.391 --> 17:09.559
You've got to put this in context that,

17:09.560 --> 17:11.361
at the time, we already knew,

17:11.363 --> 17:13.730
well, this is the most sophisticated piece of malware

17:13.732 --> 17:15.298
that we have ever seen.

17:16.066 --> 17:18.034
So it's kind of strange.

17:18.036 --> 17:23.039
Somebody takes that huge effort to hit one specific target?

17:23.307 --> 17:25.241
Well, that must be quite a significant target.

17:28.846 --> 17:31.247
Chien: <i>So at Symantec we have probes on networks</i>

17:31.249 --> 17:32.415
<i>all over the world</i>

17:32.417 --> 17:34.817
<i>watching for malicious activity.</i>

17:35.219 --> 17:37.220
O'Murchu: <i>We'd actually seen infections of STUXnet</i>

17:37.222 --> 17:39.756
<i>all over the world, in the U.S., Australia,</i>

17:39.758 --> 17:42.392
<i>in the U.K., in France, Germany, all over Europe.</i>

17:42.893 --> 17:45.293
Chien: <i>It spread to any Windows machine in the entire world.</i>

17:45.663 --> 17:47.897
You know, we had these organizations

17:47.899 --> 17:50.199
inside the United States who were in charge of

17:50.201 --> 17:51.901
<i>industrial control facilities saying,</i>

17:51.903 --> 17:53.903
<i>"we're infected. What's gonna happen?"</i>

17:54.271 --> 17:56.940
O'Murchu: <i>We didn't know if there was a deadline coming up</i>

17:56.942 --> 17:58.508
<i>where this threat would trigger</i>

17:58.510 --> 18:00.843
<i>and suddenly would, like, turn off all, you know,</i>

18:00.845 --> 18:02.412
electricity plants around the world

18:02.414 --> 18:04.180
or it would start shutting things down

18:04.182 --> 18:05.515
or launching some attack.

18:06.350 --> 18:09.385
<i>We knew that STUXnet could have very dire consequences,</i>

18:09.387 --> 18:12.055
<i>and we were very worried about</i>

18:12.057 --> 18:13.523
<i>what the payload contained</i>

18:13.525 --> 18:15.758
<i>and there was an imperative speed</i>

18:15.760 --> 18:17.860
<i>that we had to race and try and, you know,</i>

18:17.862 --> 18:19.262
<i>beat this ticking bomb.</i>

18:20.397 --> 18:22.932
<i>Eventually, we were able to refine the statistics a little</i>

18:22.934 --> 18:24.434
<i>and we saw that Iran was the number one</i>

18:24.436 --> 18:26.035
<i>infected country in the world.</i>

18:26.037 --> 18:28.605
Chien: <i>That immediately raised our eyebrows.</i>

18:28.607 --> 18:30.873
We had never seen a threat before

18:30.875 --> 18:33.009
where it was predominantly in Iran.

18:33.944 --> 18:35.545
<i>And so we began to follow what was going on</i>

18:35.547 --> 18:36.779
<i>in the geopolitical world,</i>

18:36.947 --> 18:38.547
<i>what was happening in the general news.</i>

18:38.716 --> 18:41.951
<i>And at that time, there were actually multiple explosions</i>

18:41.953 --> 18:44.854
<i>of gas pipelines going in and out of Iran.</i>

18:45.823 --> 18:47.223
<i>Unexplained explosions.</i>

18:48.759 --> 18:50.893
O'Murchu: <i>And of course, we did notice that at the time</i>

18:50.895 --> 18:53.529
<i>there had been assassinations of nuclear scientists.</i>

18:54.732 --> 18:56.165
<i>So that was worrying.</i>

18:56.967 --> 18:59.168
<i>We knew there was something bad happening.</i>

18:59.637 --> 19:01.471
Gibney: Did you get concerned for yourself?

19:01.473 --> 19:03.406
I mean, did you begin to start looking over your shoulder

19:03.408 --> 19:04.641
from time to time?

19:04.643 --> 19:06.242
Yeah, definitely looking over my shoulder

19:06.244 --> 19:08.811
and... and being careful about what I spoke about on the phone.

19:09.813 --> 19:13.016
I was... pretty confident my conversations on my...

19:13.018 --> 19:14.484
On the phone were being listened to.

19:14.818 --> 19:16.786
We were only half joking

19:16.788 --> 19:18.821
when we would look at each other

19:18.823 --> 19:20.590
and tell each other things like,

19:20.592 --> 19:22.825
"look, I'm not suicidal.

19:23.160 --> 19:26.663
If I show up dead on Monday, you know, it wasn't me."

19:35.439 --> 19:37.874
<i>We'd been publishing information about STUXnet</i>

19:37.876 --> 19:39.275
<i>all through that summer.</i>

19:40.644 --> 19:43.279
<i>And then in November, the industrial control system</i>

19:43.281 --> 19:46.416
<i>sort of expert in Holland contacted us...</i>

19:47.685 --> 19:50.286
<i>And he said all of these devices that would be inside of</i>

19:50.288 --> 19:53.356
<i>an industrial control system hold a unique identifier number</i>

19:53.358 --> 19:56.559
that identified the make and model of that device.

19:58.328 --> 20:01.998
<i>And we actually had a couple of these numbers in the code</i>

20:02.000 --> 20:03.440
<i>that we didn't know what they were.</i>

20:04.401 --> 20:06.302
And so we realized maybe what he was referring to

20:06.304 --> 20:07.770
was the magic numbers we had.

20:08.305 --> 20:09.839
And then when we searched for those magic numbers

20:09.841 --> 20:11.007
in that context,

20:11.009 --> 20:13.409
<i>we saw that what had to be connected</i>

20:13.411 --> 20:15.578
<i>to this industrial control system that was being targeted</i>

20:15.580 --> 20:17.547
<i>were something called frequency converters</i>

20:17.881 --> 20:20.049
<i>from two specific manufacturers,</i>

20:20.051 --> 20:21.818
<i>one of which was in Iran.</i>

20:22.419 --> 20:24.187
And so at this time, we absolutely knew

20:24.189 --> 20:26.522
that the facility that was being targeted

20:26.524 --> 20:27.990
had to be in Iran

20:28.325 --> 20:31.160
and had equipment made from Iranian manufacturers.

20:32.096 --> 20:33.863
When we looked up those frequency converters,

20:33.865 --> 20:35.665
<i>we immediately found out that they were actually</i>

20:35.667 --> 20:38.067
<i>export controlled by the nuclear regulatory commission.</i>

20:38.669 --> 20:40.002
<i>And that immediately lead us then</i>

20:40.004 --> 20:42.271
to some nuclear facility.

20:59.890 --> 21:02.024
Gibney: <i>This was more than a computer story,</i>

21:02.392 --> 21:04.827
<i>so I left the world of the antivirus detectives</i>

21:05.129 --> 21:07.063
<i>and sought out journalist, David Sanger,</i>

21:07.065 --> 21:09.298
<i>who specialized in the strange intersection</i>

21:09.300 --> 21:12.301
<i>of cyber, nuclear weapons, and espionage.</i>

21:13.270 --> 21:15.371
Sanger: <i>The emergence of the code</i>

21:15.373 --> 21:18.674
<i>is what put me on alert that an attack was under way.</i>

21:20.110 --> 21:23.279
<i>And because of the covert nature of the operation,</i>

21:23.281 --> 21:26.282
<i>not only were official government spokesmen</i>

21:26.284 --> 21:29.185
<i>unable to talk about it, they didn't even know about it.</i>

21:30.387 --> 21:32.455
<i>Eventually, the more I dug into it,</i>

21:32.457 --> 21:37.059
the more I began to find individuals

21:37.294 --> 21:39.495
who had been involved in some piece of it

21:39.663 --> 21:41.731
or who had witnessed some piece of it.

21:42.332 --> 21:44.734
And that meant talking to Americans,

21:44.736 --> 21:47.637
talking to Israelis, talking to Europeans,

21:47.639 --> 21:50.740
because this was obviously the first, biggest,

21:50.742 --> 21:55.311
and most sophisticated example of a state

21:55.313 --> 21:57.947
or two states using a cyber weapon

21:57.949 --> 21:59.482
for offensive purposes.

22:02.920 --> 22:05.822
<i>I came to this with a fair bit of history,</i>

22:05.824 --> 22:08.591
<i>understanding the Iranian nuclear program.</i>

22:09.626 --> 22:13.029
<i>How did Iran get its first nuclear reactor?</i>

22:13.597 --> 22:16.732
We gave it to them... under the Shah,

22:17.034 --> 22:20.469
<i>because the Shah was considered an American ally.</i>

22:21.973 --> 22:25.608
<i>Thank you again for your warm welcome, Mr. President.</i>

22:25.943 --> 22:27.543
Gary Samore: <i>During the Nixon administration,</i>

22:27.545 --> 22:30.813
<i>the U.S. was very enthusiastic about supporting</i>

22:30.815 --> 22:32.915
<i>the Shah's nuclear power program.</i>

22:33.817 --> 22:36.152
And at one point, the Nixon administration

22:36.154 --> 22:38.988
was pushing the idea that Pakistan and Iran

22:38.990 --> 22:43.593
should build a joint plant together in Iran.

22:44.962 --> 22:46.662
<i>There's at least some evidence that</i>

22:46.664 --> 22:50.166
<i>the Shah was thinking about acquisition of nuclear weapons,</i>

22:50.168 --> 22:53.703
<i>because he saw, and we were encouraging him to see Iran</i>

22:53.705 --> 22:56.005
<i>as the so-called policemen of the Persian Gulf.</i>

22:56.007 --> 22:58.174
<i>And the Iranians have always viewed themselves</i>

22:58.176 --> 23:01.410
<i>as naturally the dominant power in the Middle East.</i>

23:02.214 --> 23:07.594
Why is it normal for you,
the Germans and the British,

23:07.845 --> 23:09.435
to have...

23:10.764 --> 23:14.484
atomic and hydrogen weapons, and for Iran,

23:15.102 --> 23:17.102
the simple principle of self-defense

23:17.396 --> 23:20.106
the defense of its interests, a problem,

23:20.357 --> 23:22.357
while for others it is totally normal?

23:24.001 --> 23:25.568
Samore: <i> But the revolution,</i>

23:25.570 --> 23:27.270
<i>which overthrew the Shah in '79,</i>

23:27.272 --> 23:29.071
<i>really curtailed the program</i>

23:29.073 --> 23:31.440
<i>before it ever got any head of steam going.</i>

23:32.542 --> 23:37.113
<i>Part of our policy against Iran after the revolution</i>

23:37.115 --> 23:39.415
was to deny them nuclear technology.

23:39.417 --> 23:42.718
So most of the period when I was involved

23:42.720 --> 23:44.720
in the '80s and the '90s

23:44.722 --> 23:47.123
was the U.S. running around the world

23:47.125 --> 23:50.393
and persuading potential nuclear suppliers

23:50.395 --> 23:53.796
not to provide even peaceful nuclear technology to Iran.

23:54.031 --> 23:57.466
And what we missed was the clandestine transfer

23:57.468 --> 24:00.369
in the mid-1980s from Pakistan to Iran.

24:04.375 --> 24:05.608
Rolf Mowatt-Larssen: <i>Abdul Qadeer Khan</i>

24:05.610 --> 24:06.943
<i>is what we would call</i>

24:06.945 --> 24:08.945
<i>the father of the Pakistan nuclear program.</i>

24:10.380 --> 24:12.949
<i>He had the full authority and confidence</i>

24:12.951 --> 24:15.251
<i>of the Pakistan government from its inception</i>

24:15.253 --> 24:17.320
<i>to the production of nuclear weapons.</i>

24:19.056 --> 24:21.390
I was a CIA officer for... for...

24:21.392 --> 24:24.060
For over two decades, operations officer,

24:24.062 --> 24:25.861
worked overseas most of my career.

24:26.430 --> 24:28.497
The A.Q. Khan network is so notable

24:28.499 --> 24:31.500
because aside from building

24:31.502 --> 24:34.537
the Pakistani program for decades...

24:35.772 --> 24:38.941
It also was the means by which other countries

24:38.943 --> 24:41.577
<i>were able to develop nuclear weapons,</i>

24:41.579 --> 24:42.878
<i>including Iran.</i>

24:43.480 --> 24:45.114
Samore: <i>A.Q. Khan acting on behalf</i>

24:45.116 --> 24:46.182
<i>of the Pakistani government</i>

24:46.184 --> 24:49.285
negotiated with officials in Iran

24:49.287 --> 24:52.321
and then there was a transfer which took place

24:52.323 --> 24:53.389
through Dubai

24:53.391 --> 24:56.625
<i>of blueprints for nuclear weapons design</i>

24:56.627 --> 24:58.227
<i>as well as some hardware.</i>

24:59.363 --> 25:01.364
<i>Throughout the mid-1980s,</i>

25:01.366 --> 25:04.433
<i>the Iranian program was not very well-resourced.</i>

25:04.435 --> 25:06.268
<i>It was more of an R & D program.</i>

25:07.304 --> 25:10.506
<i>It wasn't really until the mid-'90s</i>

25:10.508 --> 25:12.775
<i>that it started to take off when they made the decision</i>

25:12.777 --> 25:14.844
<i>to build the nuclear weapons program.</i>

25:21.518 --> 25:23.019
<i>You know, we can speculate what,</i>

25:23.021 --> 25:24.453
in their mind, motivated them.

25:24.455 --> 25:27.623
I think it was the U.S. invasion of Iraq

25:27.625 --> 25:29.225
after Kuwait.

25:30.527 --> 25:31.994
<i>You know, there was an eight-year war</i>

25:31.996 --> 25:33.562
<i>between Iraq and Iran,</i>

25:33.830 --> 25:37.233
<i>we had wiped out Saddam's forces in a matter of weeks.</i>

25:40.138 --> 25:42.872
<i>And I think that was enough to convince the rulers</i>

25:42.874 --> 25:45.041
<i>in Tehran that they needed to pursue</i>

25:45.043 --> 25:46.609
<i>nuclear weapons more seriously.</i>

25:48.645 --> 25:51.547
George Bush: States like these and their terrorist allies

25:51.549 --> 25:54.383
constitute an axis of evil,

25:54.385 --> 25:57.153
arming to threaten the peace of the world.

25:58.555 --> 26:01.190
Samore: <i> From 2003 to 2005</i>

26:01.192 --> 26:04.493
<i>when they feared that the U.S. would invade them,</i>

26:04.495 --> 26:06.829
<i>they accepted limits on their nuclear program.</i>

26:07.264 --> 26:10.900
<i>But by 2006, the Iranians had come to the conclusion</i>

26:10.902 --> 26:13.769
<i>that the U.S. was bogged down in Afghanistan and Iraq</i>

26:13.771 --> 26:16.972
<i>and no longer had the capacity to threaten them,</i>

26:17.340 --> 26:21.077
<i>and so they felt it was safe to resume their enrichment program</i>

26:21.845 --> 26:24.513
<i>they started producing low enriched uranium,</i>

26:24.781 --> 26:26.782
<i>producing more centrifuges, installing them</i>

26:26.784 --> 26:30.619
<i>at the large-scale underground enrichment facility at Natanz.</i>

26:41.965 --> 26:44.414
Journalist:

26:44.414 --> 26:46.809
For a journalist, passing through
these underground tunnels

26:47.022 --> 26:50.982
and visiting the beating heart of
Iran's nuclear plant is quite an event.

26:51.193 --> 26:56.873
The president's visit to the plant today
had made this event possible for us.

26:57.825 --> 27:00.017
The West tells us that we have to
negotiate with them for like ten years

27:00.017 --> 27:02.051
Ahmadinejad:

27:02.371 --> 27:06.461
and then they will decide whether Iran
may have 20 centrifuges or not.

27:06.709 --> 27:08.669
Of course the Iranian nation
says no to them.

27:09.253 --> 27:11.003
Today, about 7,000 of these machines

27:11.296 --> 27:14.756
are working under
the ground right over there.

27:35.085 --> 27:37.019
Gibney: How many times have you been to Natanz?

27:37.354 --> 27:40.756
Not that many, because I left few years ago, the CIA,

27:40.758 --> 27:43.092
but I was there quite... quite a few times.

27:46.630 --> 27:49.198
<i>Natanz is just in the middle of the desert.</i>

27:51.134 --> 27:53.102
<i>When they were building it in secret,</i>

27:53.336 --> 27:57.373
<i>they were calling it desert irrigation facility.</i>

27:57.874 --> 27:59.441
For the local people,

27:59.443 --> 28:02.011
you want to sell why you are building a big complex.

28:04.814 --> 28:07.516
<i>There is a lot of artillery and air force.</i>

28:07.518 --> 28:11.921
<i>It's better protected against attack from air</i>

28:12.455 --> 28:14.957
<i>than any other nuclear installation I have seen.</i>

28:17.727 --> 28:20.196
<i>So this is deeply underground.</i>

28:24.801 --> 28:28.704
But then inside, Natanz is like any other centrifuge facility.

28:28.706 --> 28:33.042
I have been all over the world, from Brazil to Russia, Japan,

28:33.044 --> 28:37.580
so they are all alike with their own features,

28:37.582 --> 28:39.982
their own centrifuges, their own culture,

28:39.984 --> 28:42.585
but basically, the process is the same.

28:43.653 --> 28:46.722
<i>And so are the monitoring activities of the IAEA.</i>

28:46.724 --> 28:48.390
<i>There are basic principles.</i>

28:48.392 --> 28:51.126
<i>You want to see what goes in, what goes out,</i>

28:51.394 --> 28:53.562
<i>and then on top of that you make sure that</i>

28:53.564 --> 28:56.031
<i>it produces low enriched uranium</i>

28:56.033 --> 28:58.434
<i>instead of anything to do with the higher enrichments</i>

28:58.436 --> 29:00.603
<i>and nuclear weapon grade uranium.</i>

29:06.576 --> 29:07.943
Emad Kiyaei: <i>Iran's nuclear facilities</i>

29:07.945 --> 29:10.179
<i>are under 24-hour watch.</i>

29:10.880 --> 29:13.215
<i>Of the United Nations nuclear watchdog,</i>

29:13.217 --> 29:16.518
<i>the IAEA, the International Atomic Energy Agency.</i>

29:17.887 --> 29:22.091
Every single gram of Iranian fissile material...

29:23.293 --> 29:24.660
Is accounted for.

29:27.464 --> 29:29.932
<i>They have, like, basically seals they put</i>

29:29.934 --> 29:33.502
<i>on fissile materials. There are IAEA seals.</i>

29:33.737 --> 29:36.038
You can't break it

29:36.040 --> 29:37.873
without getting noticed.

29:39.876 --> 29:42.111
Heinonen: <i>When you look at the uranium</i>

29:42.113 --> 29:45.981
<i>which was there in Natanz, it was a very special uranium.</i>

29:46.149 --> 29:51.553
This is called Isotope 236, and that was a puzzle to us,

29:51.555 --> 29:53.989
because you only see this sort of uranium

29:53.991 --> 29:57.126
in states which have had nuclear weapons.

29:58.995 --> 30:01.697
<i>We realized that they had cheated us.</i>

30:02.399 --> 30:05.668
<i>This sort of equipment has been bought</i>

30:05.670 --> 30:07.469
from what they call a black market.

30:07.471 --> 30:10.706
They never pointed out it to A.Q. Khan

30:11.141 --> 30:12.941
at that point of time.

30:17.814 --> 30:21.150
<i>What I was surprised was the sophistication</i>

30:21.152 --> 30:22.985
<i>and the quality control</i>

30:23.286 --> 30:25.287
<i>and the way they have the manufacturing</i>

30:25.289 --> 30:26.689
<i>was really professional.</i>

30:27.824 --> 30:30.426
It was not something, you know, you just create

30:30.428 --> 30:31.960
in a few months' time.

30:31.962 --> 30:34.697
This was a result of a long process.

30:41.805 --> 30:44.606
<i>A centrifuge, you feed uranium gas</i>

30:44.608 --> 30:47.710
<i>in and you have a cascade, thousands of centrifuges,</i>

30:47.712 --> 30:50.713
<i>and from the other end you get enriched uranium out.</i>

30:51.448 --> 30:55.451
<i>It separates uranium based on spinning the rotors.</i>

30:55.453 --> 30:59.221
<i>It spins so fast, 300 meters per second,</i>

30:59.223 --> 31:02.257
<i>the same as the velocity of sound.</i>

31:03.626 --> 31:05.294
<i>These are tremendous forces</i>

31:05.296 --> 31:08.230
<i>and as a result, the rotor, it twists,</i>

31:08.232 --> 31:10.399
<i>looks like a banana at one point of time.</i>

31:11.801 --> 31:13.369
So it has to be balanced

31:13.371 --> 31:16.739
because any small vibration it will blow up.

31:18.141 --> 31:20.075
<i>And here comes another trouble.</i>

31:20.377 --> 31:22.544
<i>You have to raise the temperature</i>

31:22.546 --> 31:25.647
<i>but this very thin rotor was...</i>

31:25.649 --> 31:27.683
<i>They are made from carbon fiber,</i>

31:27.685 --> 31:30.319
<i>and the other pieces, they are made from metal.</i>

31:31.221 --> 31:34.723
When you heat carbon fiber, it shrinks.

31:35.825 --> 31:38.127
When you heat metal, it expands.

31:38.495 --> 31:41.530
So you need to balance not only that they spin,

31:41.532 --> 31:44.666
they twist, but this temperature behavior

31:44.668 --> 31:46.902
<i>in such a way that it doesn't break.</i>

31:46.904 --> 31:49.104
<i>So this has to be very precise.</i>

31:49.606 --> 31:52.074
<i>This is what makes them very difficult to manufacture.</i>

31:52.076 --> 31:54.743
You can model it, you can calculate it,

31:54.745 --> 31:57.212
but at the very end, it's actually based

31:57.214 --> 31:59.848
on practice and experience.

31:59.850 --> 32:03.152
So it's a... it's a piece of art, so to say.

32:13.631 --> 32:16.454
Man:

32:16.454 --> 32:19.690
Because of the strength of our nation,
our army and our revolutionary guard

32:20.939 --> 32:26.569
Our dawn became eternal
by the glow of success

32:28.113 --> 32:31.993
Morning of dreams rises from the shores

32:32.242 --> 32:36.162
The branches of life have sprouted

32:36.497 --> 32:42.127
May this victory be Blessed

32:44.093 --> 32:46.428
Heinonen: <i>Iranians are very proud of their centrifuges.</i>

32:46.430 --> 32:49.398
<i>They have a lot of public relations videos</i>

32:49.400 --> 32:53.135
<i>given up always in April when they have what they call</i>

32:53.137 --> 32:54.636
<i>a national nuclear day.</i>

32:55.057 --> 32:57.347
Blessed be this holy spring

32:57.347 --> 32:59.141
Man:

32:59.311 --> 33:02.151
Blessed be the gardener

33:02.439 --> 33:05.069
I proudly announce that from today on,

33:05.442 --> 33:08.952
Iran is among the countries
that can produce nuclear fuel.

33:08.953 --> 33:12.321
Kiyaei: <i>Ahmadinejad came into his presidency saying</i>

33:12.323 --> 33:14.923
if the international community wants to derail us

33:14.925 --> 33:16.592
we will stand up to it.

33:17.660 --> 33:20.362
If they want us to sign more inspections

33:20.364 --> 33:23.632
and more additional protocols and other measures,

33:23.634 --> 33:26.368
no, we will not. We will fight for our rights.

33:27.605 --> 33:30.672
<i>Iran is a signature to nuclear non-proliferation treaty,</i>

33:30.674 --> 33:34.276
<i>and under that treaty, Iran has a right to a nuclear program.</i>

33:34.844 --> 33:38.313
<i>We can have enrichment. Who are you, world powers,</i>

33:38.315 --> 33:40.782
<i>to come and tell us that we cannot have enrichment?</i>

33:41.150 --> 33:42.885
This was his mantra,

33:43.620 --> 33:46.989
and it galvanized the public.

33:50.560 --> 33:52.961
Sanger: <i> By 2007, 2008,</i>

33:52.963 --> 33:55.464
<i>the U.S. government was in a very bad place with</i>

33:55.466 --> 33:56.765
<i>the Iranian program.</i>

33:57.734 --> 33:59.835
<i>President Bush recognized</i>

33:59.837 --> 34:02.471
<i>that he could not even come out in public</i>

34:02.473 --> 34:04.973
<i>and declare that the Iranians were building a nuclear weapon,</i>

34:04.975 --> 34:06.808
<i>because by this time, he had gone through</i>

34:06.810 --> 34:10.112
<i>the entire WMD fiasco in Iraq.</i>

34:10.813 --> 34:13.081
He could not really take military action.

34:13.083 --> 34:15.484
<i>Condoleezza Rice said to him at one point,</i>

34:15.485 --> 34:18.887
<i>"you know, Mr. President, I think you've invaded</i>

34:18.889 --> 34:22.558
<i>your last Muslim country, even for the best of reasons."</i>

34:24.393 --> 34:26.594
<i>He didn't want to let the Israelis</i>

34:26.597 --> 34:28.429
<i>conduct a military operation.</i>

34:28.764 --> 34:34.503
It's 1938, and Iran is Germany and it's racing...

34:35.338 --> 34:37.940
To arm itself with atomic bombs.

34:38.541 --> 34:42.110
Iran's nuclear ambitions must be stopped.

34:42.779 --> 34:47.516
They have to be stopped. We all have to stop it, now.

34:47.518 --> 34:50.118
That's the one message I have for you today.

34:50.120 --> 34:52.020
- Thank you.

34:52.022 --> 34:54.889
Israel was saying they were gonna bomb Iran.

34:54.891 --> 34:58.093
And the government here in Washington

34:58.095 --> 35:00.462
did all sorts of scenarios about what would happen

35:00.464 --> 35:03.031
if that Israeli attack occurred.

35:03.433 --> 35:05.601
They were all very ugly scenarios.

35:05.603 --> 35:08.604
Our belief was that if they went on their own

35:08.606 --> 35:10.405
knowing the limitations...

35:10.407 --> 35:12.307
No, they're a very good air force, all right?

35:12.642 --> 35:14.710
But it's small and the distances are great

35:14.712 --> 35:17.112
and the target's disbursed and hardened, all right?

35:18.114 --> 35:20.682
If they would have attempted a raid

35:21.384 --> 35:23.118
on a military plane,

35:23.419 --> 35:26.221
we would have been assuming that they were assuming

35:26.223 --> 35:28.790
we would finish that which they started.

35:28.792 --> 35:31.426
In other words, there would be many of us

35:31.428 --> 35:33.462
in government thinking that the purpose of the raid

35:33.464 --> 35:35.998
wasn't to destroy the Iranian nuclear system,

35:36.000 --> 35:39.668
but the purpose of the raid was to put us at war with Iran.

35:40.603 --> 35:42.638
Israel is very much concerned about

35:42.640 --> 35:45.307
Iran's nuclear program, more than the United States.

35:45.309 --> 35:48.076
It's only natural because of the size of the country,

35:48.078 --> 35:50.479
because we live in this neighborhood,

35:50.481 --> 35:54.116
America lives thousands and thousands miles away from Iran.

35:54.118 --> 35:57.753
The two countries agreed on the goal.

35:58.021 --> 36:00.789
There is no page between us

36:00.791 --> 36:06.128
that Iran should not have a nuclear military capability.

36:06.130 --> 36:08.130
There are some differences

36:08.132 --> 36:10.499
on how to... how to achieve it

36:10.501 --> 36:12.801
and when action is needed.

36:15.424 --> 36:21.054
The origin of corruption (Israel)
will be wiped off the face of the Earth.

36:22.311 --> 36:24.713
Yadlin: <i>We are taking very seriously</i>

36:24.715 --> 36:27.449
leaders of countries who call to the destruction

36:27.451 --> 36:30.085
and annihilation of our people.

36:30.286 --> 36:32.788
If Iran will get nuclear weapons,

36:32.790 --> 36:34.256
now or in the future...

36:35.224 --> 36:38.060
It means that for the first time in human history

36:38.861 --> 36:41.563
Islamic zealots, religious zealots,

36:42.231 --> 36:44.566
will get their hand on

36:44.568 --> 36:47.536
the most dangerous, devastating weapons,

36:47.538 --> 36:50.305
and the world should prevent this.

36:52.475 --> 36:56.244
Samore: <i>The Israelis believe that the Iranian leadership</i>

36:56.246 --> 36:59.181
<i>has already made the decision to build nuclear weapons</i>

36:59.183 --> 37:01.083
<i>when they think they can get away with it.</i>

37:01.484 --> 37:04.252
<i>The view in the U.S. is that the Iranians</i>

37:04.254 --> 37:06.421
<i>haven't made that final decision yet.</i>

37:07.390 --> 37:09.324
To me, that doesn't make any difference.

37:09.326 --> 37:11.059
I mean, it really doesn't make any difference,

37:11.061 --> 37:14.229
and it's probably unknowable, unless you can put, you know,

37:14.231 --> 37:17.599
Supreme Leader Khamenei on the couch and interview him.

37:17.601 --> 37:20.535
<i>I think, you know, from our standpoint,</i>

37:20.537 --> 37:23.171
<i>stopping Iran from getting the threshold capacity</i>

37:23.173 --> 37:26.308
<i>is, you know, the primary policy objective.</i>

37:27.610 --> 37:29.711
<i>Once they have the fissile material,</i>

37:29.713 --> 37:32.114
<i>once they have the capacity to produce nuclear weapons,</i>

37:32.116 --> 37:33.482
<i>then the game is lost.</i>

37:39.288 --> 37:41.089
Hayden: <i>President Bush once said to me, he said,</i>

37:41.091 --> 37:44.192
<i>"Mike, I don't want any president ever to be faced</i>

37:44.194 --> 37:48.230
with only two options, bombing or the bomb."

37:48.232 --> 37:49.464
Right?

37:49.466 --> 37:53.034
He... he wanted options that... that made it...

37:53.236 --> 37:56.204
Made it far less likely he or his successor

37:56.206 --> 37:58.740
or successors would ever get to that point

37:58.742 --> 38:00.375
where that's... that's all you've got.

38:00.710 --> 38:04.346
We wanted to be energetic enough in pursuing this problem

38:04.714 --> 38:07.716
that... that the Israelis would certainly believe,

38:07.718 --> 38:08.917
"yeah, we get it."

38:08.919 --> 38:11.052
The intelligence cooperation between Israel

38:11.054 --> 38:14.489
and the United States is very, very good.

38:15.258 --> 38:17.559
<i>And therefore, the Israelis went to the Americans</i>

38:17.561 --> 38:21.163
<i>and said, "okay, guys, you don't want us to bomb Iran.</i>

38:21.165 --> 38:24.332
<i>Okay, let's do it differently."</i>

38:24.834 --> 38:28.403
<i>And then the American intelligence community started</i>

38:28.405 --> 38:30.105
<i>rolling in joint forces</i>

38:30.107 --> 38:32.073
<i>with the Israeli intelligence community.</i>

38:32.742 --> 38:36.745
One day a group of intelligence and military officials showed up

38:37.446 --> 38:39.381
in President Bush's office

38:39.982 --> 38:41.516
and said, "sir, we have an idea.

38:42.652 --> 38:43.985
It's a big risk.

38:44.520 --> 38:46.321
It might not work, but here it is."

38:53.863 --> 38:57.499
Langner: <i>Moving forward in my analysis of the codes,</i>

38:57.501 --> 39:01.536
<i>I took a closer look at the photographs</i>

39:01.538 --> 39:03.371
<i>that had been published</i>

39:03.373 --> 39:08.143
by the Iranians themselves in a press tour from 2008

39:08.145 --> 39:11.279
<i>of Ahmadinejad and the shiny centrifuges.</i>

39:13.683 --> 39:15.550
Sanger: <i>Well, photographs of Ahmadinejad</i>

39:15.552 --> 39:18.353
<i>going through the centrifuges at Natanz</i>

39:18.355 --> 39:21.790
<i>had provided some very important clues.</i>

39:22.491 --> 39:24.693
There was a huge amount to be learned.

39:33.002 --> 39:35.804
<i>First of all, those photographs showed</i>

39:35.806 --> 39:39.140
<i>many of the individuals who were guiding Ahmadinejad</i>

39:39.142 --> 39:40.308
<i>through the program.</i>

39:40.310 --> 39:42.911
<i>And there's one very famous photograph that shows</i>

39:42.913 --> 39:44.913
<i>Ahmadinejad being shown something.</i>

39:44.915 --> 39:47.482
<i>You see his face, you can't see what's on the computer.</i>

39:47.484 --> 39:50.919
<i>And one of the scientists who was behind him</i>

39:50.921 --> 39:53.321
<i>was assassinated a few months later.</i>

39:57.693 --> 39:59.427
Langner: <i>In one of those photographs,</i>

39:59.695 --> 40:03.031
you could see parts of a computer screen.

40:03.033 --> 40:05.600
We... we refer to that as a SCADA screen.

40:05.602 --> 40:08.570
<i>The SCADA system is basically a piece of software</i>

40:08.572 --> 40:10.171
<i>running on a computer.</i>

40:10.173 --> 40:13.775
<i>It enables the operators to monitor the processes.</i>

40:14.777 --> 40:18.914
What you could see when you look close enough

40:19.448 --> 40:23.785
<i>was a more detailed view of the configuration</i>

40:24.587 --> 40:27.889
<i>there were these six groups of centrifuges</i>

40:27.891 --> 40:31.326
<i>and each group had 164 entries.</i>

40:31.894 --> 40:33.461
And guess what?

40:33.763 --> 40:36.097
That was a perfect match to what we saw

40:36.099 --> 40:37.465
in the attack code.

40:38.801 --> 40:42.203
<i>It was absolutely clear that this piece of code</i>

40:42.205 --> 40:45.774
<i>was attacking an array of six different groups</i>

40:45.776 --> 40:49.611
<i>of, let's just say, thingies, physical objects,</i>

40:49.613 --> 40:55.517
<i>and in those six groups, there were 164 elements.</i>

40:59.221 --> 41:01.556
Gibney: Were you able to do any actual physical tests?

41:01.558 --> 41:03.792
Or it was all just code analysis?

41:03.794 --> 41:05.727
Yeah, so, you know, we obviously

41:05.729 --> 41:08.797
couldn't set up our own sort of nuclear enrichment facility.

41:08.965 --> 41:11.266
So... but what we did was we did obtain some PLCs,

41:11.268 --> 41:12.500
the exact models.

41:19.675 --> 41:22.077
<i>We then ordered an air pump, and that's what we used</i>

41:22.079 --> 41:23.745
<i>sort of as our sort of proof of concept.</i>

41:24.580 --> 41:26.314
O'Murchu: <i>We needed a visual demonstration</i>

41:26.316 --> 41:28.516
<i>to show people what we discovered.</i>

41:28.818 --> 41:30.852
So we thought of different things that we could do,

41:30.854 --> 41:32.988
and we... we settled on blowing up a balloon.

41:37.326 --> 41:39.294
<i>We were able to write a program that would inflate a balloon,</i>

41:39.296 --> 41:42.197
<i>and it was set to stop after five seconds.</i>

41:52.174 --> 41:53.942
<i>So it would inflate the balloon to a certain size</i>

41:53.944 --> 41:55.443
<i>but it wouldn't burst the balloon</i>

41:55.445 --> 41:56.878
<i>and it was all safe.</i>

41:56.880 --> 41:58.980
And we showed everybody, this is the code

41:58.982 --> 42:00.215
that's on the PLC.

42:00.649 --> 42:02.617
<i>And the timer says, "stop after five seconds."</i>

42:02.852 --> 42:04.412
<i>We know that's what's going to happen.</i>

42:04.987 --> 42:07.255
And then we would infect the computer with STUXnet,

42:07.790 --> 42:10.058
<i>and we would run the test again.</i>

42:41.257 --> 42:42.857
Here is a piece of software

42:42.859 --> 42:45.827
that should only exist in a cyber realm

42:45.829 --> 42:48.930
and it is able to affect physical equipment

42:48.932 --> 42:52.667
in a plant or factory and cause physical damage.

42:52.669 --> 42:54.736
Real-world physical destruction.

42:59.241 --> 43:01.910
<i>At that time, things became very scary to us.</i>

43:01.912 --> 43:04.412
<i>Here you had malware potentially killing people</i>

43:04.414 --> 43:06.714
and that was something that was always Hollywood-esque to us

43:06.716 --> 43:07.882
that we'd always laugh at

43:07.884 --> 43:09.918
when people made that kind of assertion.

43:15.524 --> 43:18.026
Gibney: <i>At this point, you had to have started developing</i>

43:18.028 --> 43:20.795
<i>theories as to who had built STUXnet.</i>

43:21.730 --> 43:23.298
It wasn't lost on us that

43:23.300 --> 43:26.534
there were probably only a few countries

43:26.536 --> 43:28.870
in the world that would want

43:28.872 --> 43:31.739
and have the motivation to sabotage

43:31.741 --> 43:33.875
Iran's nuclear enrichment facility.

43:33.877 --> 43:35.777
The U.S. government would be up there.

43:35.779 --> 43:37.946
Israeli government certainly would be... would be up there.

43:37.948 --> 43:40.048
You know, maybe U.K., France, Germany,

43:40.050 --> 43:41.483
those sorts of countries,

43:41.485 --> 43:43.785
but we never found any information that

43:43.787 --> 43:46.821
would tie it back 100 percent to... to those countries.

43:46.823 --> 43:48.756
There are no telltale signs.

43:48.758 --> 43:51.326
You know, the attackers don't leave a message inside

43:51.328 --> 43:53.495
saying, you know, "it was me."

43:54.396 --> 43:57.665
And even if they did, all of that stuff can be faked.

43:58.000 --> 44:00.668
So it's very, very difficult to do attribution

44:00.670 --> 44:02.403
when looking at computer code.

44:03.272 --> 44:04.806
Gibney: Subsequent work that's been done

44:04.808 --> 44:07.242
leads us to believe that this was the work of

44:07.244 --> 44:08.776
a collaboration between Israel and the United States.

44:08.778 --> 44:09.844
Yeah, yeah.

44:09.846 --> 44:10.979
Gibney: Did you have any evidence

44:10.981 --> 44:12.247
in terms of your analysis

44:12.249 --> 44:14.249
that would lead you to believe that

44:14.251 --> 44:15.583
that's correct also?

44:15.585 --> 44:17.685
Nothing that I could talk about on camera.

44:19.188 --> 44:21.990
Gibney: Well, can I ask why?

44:21.992 --> 44:23.825
No.

44:23.827 --> 44:25.527
Well, you can, but I won't answer.

44:27.964 --> 44:30.265
Gibney: But even in the case of nation-states,

44:30.267 --> 44:31.766
I mean, one of the concerns is...

44:31.768 --> 44:33.902
Gibney: <i>This was beginning to really piss me off.</i>

44:34.336 --> 44:37.672
<i>Even civilians with an interest in telling the STUXnet story</i>

44:37.674 --> 44:40.608
<i>were refusing to address the role of Tel Aviv</i>

44:40.610 --> 44:43.845
<i>and Washington. But luckily for me,</i>

44:44.113 --> 44:45.947
<i>while D.C. is a city of secrets,</i>

44:46.282 --> 44:48.049
<i>it is also a city of leaks.</i>

44:48.517 --> 44:50.218
<i>They're as regular as a heartbeat</i>

44:50.220 --> 44:51.953
<i>and just as hard to stop.</i>

44:52.955 --> 44:54.522
<i>That's what I was counting on.</i>

44:59.696 --> 45:03.231
<i>Finally, after speaking to a number of people on background,</i>

45:03.233 --> 45:05.833
<i>I did find a way of confirming, on the record,</i>

45:05.835 --> 45:07.702
<i>the American role in STUXnet.</i>

45:08.671 --> 45:10.805
<i>In exchange for details of the operation,</i>

45:10.807 --> 45:12.874
<i>I had to agree to find a way</i>

45:12.876 --> 45:15.176
<i>to disguise the source of the information.</i>

45:15.178 --> 45:16.945
- Gibney: <i>We're good?</i>
- Man: <i> We're on.</i>

45:18.514 --> 45:20.181
Gibney: <i>So the first question I have to ask you</i>

45:20.183 --> 45:21.583
<i>is about secrecy.</i>

45:22.084 --> 45:25.153
<i>I mean, at this point, everyone knows about STUXnet.</i>

45:25.155 --> 45:26.821
<i>Why can't we talk about it?</i>

45:27.323 --> 45:28.690
<i>It's a covert operation.</i>

45:28.692 --> 45:30.491
Gibney: <i> Not anymore.</i>

45:30.493 --> 45:32.794
<i>I mean, we know what happened, we know who did it.</i>

45:33.028 --> 45:35.730
<i>Well, maybe you don't know as much as you think you know.</i>

45:36.532 --> 45:39.100
Gibney: <i>Well, I'm talking to you because I want to</i>

45:39.102 --> 45:40.501
<i>get the story right.</i>

45:40.503 --> 45:42.463
<i>Well, that's the same reason I'm talking to you.</i>

45:44.707 --> 45:46.507
Gibney: <i>Even though it's a covert operation?</i>

45:47.543 --> 45:51.379
<i>Look, this is not a Snowden kind of thing, okay?</i>

45:51.381 --> 45:52.714
<i>I think what he did was wrong.</i>

45:52.716 --> 45:55.850
<i>He went too far. He gave away too much.</i>

45:56.352 --> 45:58.353
<i>Unlike Snowden, who was a contractor,</i>

45:58.355 --> 46:00.121
<i>I was in NSA.</i>

46:00.756 --> 46:02.957
<i>I believe in the agency, so what I'm willing to give you</i>

46:02.959 --> 46:04.592
<i>will be limited, but we're talking</i>

46:04.594 --> 46:06.427
<i>because everyone's getting the story wrong</i>

46:06.429 --> 46:08.029
<i>and we have to get it right.</i>

46:08.031 --> 46:09.797
<i>We have to understand these new weapons.</i>

46:09.799 --> 46:11.065
<i>The stakes are too high.</i>

46:11.067 --> 46:12.367
Gibney: <i> What do you mean?</i>

46:14.470 --> 46:16.437
<i>We did STUXnet.</i>

46:17.640 --> 46:18.806
<i>It's a fact.</i>

46:18.808 --> 46:22.543
<i>You know, we came so fucking close to disaster,</i>

46:22.545 --> 46:24.212
<i>and we're still on the edge.</i>

46:25.748 --> 46:30.818
<i>It was a huge multinational, interagency operation.</i>

46:32.087 --> 46:34.789
<i>In the U.S. it was CIA,</i>

46:35.257 --> 46:38.726
<i>NSA, and the military Cyber Command.</i>

46:39.228 --> 46:42.897
<i>From Britain, we used Iran intel out of GCHQ,</i>

46:43.499 --> 46:45.333
<i>but the main partner was Israel.</i>

46:45.335 --> 46:46.834
<i>Over there, Mossad ran the show,</i>

46:46.836 --> 46:49.570
<i>and the technical work was done by Unit 8200.</i>

46:50.506 --> 46:53.508
