53:31.574 --> 53:34.175
that we always assumed that we were successful

53:34.177 --> 53:35.910
at defending things at the barrier,

53:35.912 --> 53:38.079
at the... at the kind of perimeter that we might have

53:38.081 --> 53:40.081
between our networks and the outside world,

53:40.083 --> 53:42.149
there was a large confidence

53:42.151 --> 53:44.318
that we'd been mostly successful.

53:44.653 --> 53:46.220
But that was a moment in time when we came to

53:46.222 --> 53:49.790
the quick conclusion that it... it's not really ever secure.

53:50.659 --> 53:53.360
<i>That then accelerated The Department of Defense's</i>

53:53.362 --> 53:54.929
<i>progress towards what ultimately</i>

53:54.931 --> 53:56.063
<i>became Cyber Command.</i>

53:59.367 --> 54:00.568
Good morning.

