54:44.781 --> 54:46.480
is sitting out at Fort Meade on top of

54:46.482 --> 54:48.215
The National Security Agency,

54:48.217 --> 54:50.985
because NSA has the abilities to do these things.

54:51.286 --> 54:54.088
Cyber Command has the authority to do these things.

54:54.090 --> 54:57.324
And "these things" here refer to the cyber-attack.

54:57.326 --> 54:59.360
This is a huge change

54:59.995 --> 55:03.664
for the nature of the intelligence agencies.

55:04.099 --> 55:06.901
<i>The NSA was supposed to be a code-making</i>

55:06.903 --> 55:09.270
<i>and code-breaking operation</i>

55:09.272 --> 55:13.440
<i>to monitor the communications of foreign powers</i>

55:13.442 --> 55:14.842
<i>and American adversaries</i>

55:14.844 --> 55:17.178
<i>in the defense of the United States.</i>

55:17.679 --> 55:21.182
<i>But creating a Cyber Command meant using</i>

55:21.184 --> 55:24.218
<i>the same technology to do offense.</i>

55:26.354 --> 55:30.357
<i>Once you get inside an adversary's computer networks,</i>

55:30.359 --> 55:33.194
<i>you put an implant in that network.</i>

55:33.428 --> 55:36.030
<i>And we have tens of thousands of foreign computers</i>

55:36.032 --> 55:38.766
<i>and networks that the United States put implants in.</i>

55:39.534 --> 55:42.536
<i>You can use it to monitor what's going across</i>

55:42.538 --> 55:44.538
<i>that network and you can use it</i>

55:44.540 --> 55:47.775
<i>to insert cyber weapons, malware.</i>

55:48.877 --> 55:52.079
If you can spy on a network, you can manipulate it.

55:52.781 --> 55:54.515
It's already included.

55:54.716 --> 55:57.051
The only thing you need is an act of will.

56:01.057 --> 56:02.857
NSA source: <i>I played a role in Iraq.</i>

56:02.859 --> 56:05.226
<i>I can't tell you whether it was military or not,</i>

56:05.228 --> 56:06.827
<i>but I can tell you</i>

56:06.829 --> 56:09.163
<i>NSA had combat support teams in country.</i>

56:10.700 --> 56:13.367
<i>And for the first time, units in the field</i>

56:13.369 --> 56:15.769
<i>had direct access to NSA intel.</i>

56:18.341 --> 56:20.207
<i>Over time, we thought more about offense</i>

56:20.209 --> 56:21.675
<i>than defense, you know,</i>

56:21.677 --> 56:23.410
<i>more about attacking than intelligence.</i>

56:24.713 --> 56:27.748
<i>In the old days, sigint units would try to track radios,</i>

56:27.750 --> 56:30.017
<i>but through NSA in Iraq,</i>

56:30.019 --> 56:32.052
<i>we had access to all the networks</i>

56:32.054 --> 56:33.587
<i>going in and out of the country.</i>

56:33.589 --> 56:35.656
<i>And we hoovered up every text message,</i>

56:35.658 --> 56:37.157
<i>email, and phone call.</i>

56:37.692 --> 56:40.094
<i>A complete surveillance state.</i>

56:40.996 --> 56:45.065
<i>We could find the bad guys, say, a gang making IEDs,</i>

56:45.067 --> 56:48.602
<i>map their networks, and follow them in real time.</i>

56:48.604 --> 56:49.904
Soldier: <i> Roger.</i>

56:49.906 --> 56:51.705
NSA source: <i>And we could lock into cell phones</i>

56:51.707 --> 56:53.774
<i>even when they were off and send a fake text</i>

56:53.776 --> 56:56.210
<i>from a friend, suggest a meeting place,</i>

56:56.212 --> 56:58.078
<i>and then capture...</i>

56:58.080 --> 56:59.446
Soldier: <i> 1A, clear to fire.</i>

56:59.915 --> 57:01.215
<i>...or kill.</i>

57:01.217 --> 57:02.316
Soldier: <i> Good shot.</i>

57:05.353 --> 57:07.621
Brown: <i>A lot of the people that came to Cyber Command,</i>

57:07.623 --> 57:09.456
<i>the military guys, came directly from</i>

57:09.458 --> 57:11.458
<i>an assignment in Afghanistan or Iraq,</i>

57:11.460 --> 57:14.028
<i>'cause those are the people with experience</i>

57:14.030 --> 57:15.963
<i>and expertise in operations,</i>

57:15.965 --> 57:17.898
and those are the ones you want looking at this

57:17.900 --> 57:19.934
to see how cyber could facilitate

57:19.936 --> 57:22.169
traditional military operations.

